{
  "texts": [
    "JHEP04(2024)048number of zeroes and P (ω +) the number of poles on the whole of Σ g, counting multiplicity.",
    "We would like the zeroes away from insertion points, but let's first find P (ω +) so that we can use this formula.",
    "Recall from (3.9) that as z → z i, we have the OPEξ + (z) V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i) = (z -z i) -w i +1 2 V w i m i 1,m i2 +1/2 +... By Wick's theorem, the only other places we could possibly have poles in ω + (z) are at the insertion points {u α }.",
    "However, from σ2 (ξ ±)(z) = zξ ± (z), we know that ξ + (z)W (u α) = O((z -u α)).Therefore, P (ω +) = n i=1 w i +12, whilst there are n + 2g -2 simple zeroes coming from the insertion points {u α }.",
    "We deduce that Z(ω +) = g -1 + n i=1 w i +12."
  ]
}